                    <h3 style="padding:0;width:100%;font-family:Georgia, 'Times New Roman', Times, serif;font-weight:700;font-size:16px;color:#93888F;line-height:23.1px;text-align: left;margin:0;text-transform:uppercase">Telecoms</h3>
                </div>
                <div style="width:100%;background-color: transparent">
                    <h3 style="width:100%;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-size:16px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;font-weight:700;color:#28121F;line-height:20px;text-transform:capitalize;letter-spacing:-0.32px;text-align:left">Nigeria is trying to upgrade its Internet connection
                    </h3>
                    <div style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size:16px;line-height:25.6px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px">
<figure style="width: 100%;padding-bottom:16px;text-align:left;margin:0">

<a href="https://techcabal.com/category/newsletters/tc-daily/">
<img decoding="async" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://beehiiv-images-production.s3.amazonaws.com/uploads/asset/file/28f1f0be-c160-4b6e-a9fc-715a91fd18c0/NCC-2-1.png?t=1777269149" width="100%" height="auto" style="object-fit: cover"></a>
<figcaption style="color:#808080;font-size:12px;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;line-height:19.8px;padding-top:6px;font-weight:400">Image Source: BusinessDay
</figcaption>
</figure>
                        
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0">The Nigerian Communications Commission (NCC), the country&#8217;s telecoms regulator, <a href="https://techcabal.com/2026/04/24/nigeria-launches-three-year-plan-to-upgrade-internet-system/" style="text-decoration: underline;color: #b61313 !important">has set up</a> a national council to upgrade the country&rsquo;s Internet system that can support far more devices, data, and modern services.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0"><strong>What is to change? </strong>Nigeria currently heavily uses the Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) system, an older Internet system which has been in use since the 1980s. This system assigns addresses to devices so that they can connect online (IP address). But it can only support a limited number of devices, a limit which we&#8217;ve basically hit. The Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6) is the upgrade-the latest global standard for identifying and routing devices. It removes that device limit almost entirely and allows every device to have its own unique address</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0"><strong>Why now? </strong>Internet usage in Nigeria is climbing fast. In January 2026, total Internet consumption reached 1.39 million terabytes (TB), 38.4% more than the previous year. Add 5G, cloud services, AI tools, and more connected devices, and the pressure on existing infrastructure becomes obvious. This upgrade is about keeping the Internet functional as demand keeps rising.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0"><strong>The plan and the challenge: </strong>The NCC has set up a council to drive this transition and lead with government systems first. Then it will push adoption to other telcos, banks, government agencies, and tech players.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0">However, Nigeria has attempted major infrastructure upgrades before, like fibre expansion projects and satellite plans that stalled. IPv6 is even more complex because during the transition, organisations must run both IPv4 and IPv6 at the same time.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0">Many security systems (firewalls, fraud detection tools, and network monitoring systems) today are set up to monitor IPv4 traffic. If IPv6 traffic isn&rsquo;t properly configured and monitored, it can slip past existing security controls unnoticed, meaning suspicious activity might not be flagged as quickly, or at all, creating new risks for regulators and service providers to manage. For users, it could translate to things like delayed fraud detection and data exposure.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0"><strong>What should you expect? </strong>If you&rsquo;re using a relatively new phone or laptop, you&rsquo;re likely fine, as most modern devices already support IPv6. Older devices and networks may struggle. That doesn&rsquo;t mean your Internet will stop working, but you might start to notice differences over time, like slower connections. In the long run, this upgrade is expected to make the Internet faster and more reliable.</p>
